.TH PATHSEARCH 1 "January 2026" "pathsearch 0.2.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
pathsearch \- search for executables in PATH
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B pathsearch
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] [\fIPATTERN\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B pathsearch
searches each directory in the PATH environment variable for executable
files matching the given pattern. Results are displayed in PATH order,
so the first result is the executable that would run if you typed the
command.
.PP
If no pattern is provided, all executables in PATH are listed.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-r ", " \-\-regex
Interpret the pattern as a regular expression instead of a substring.
.TP
.BR \-\-color " " \fIWHEN\fR
Control color output. WHEN can be \fBauto\fR (default), \fBalways\fR, or \fBnever\fR.
Auto enables color when output is a terminal.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print help information.
.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-version
Print version information.
.SH PATTERN MATCHING
By default, pathsearch performs case-sensitive substring matching.
.PP
With \fB\-r\fR, the pattern is interpreted as a regular expression.
Use \fB^pattern\fR to match at the start of filenames, or
\fBpattern$\fR to match at the end.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Find executables containing "vim":
.B pathsearch vim
.TP
Find executables starting with "python":
.B pathsearch \-r \(aq^python\(aq
.TP
List all executables:
.B pathsearch
.TP
Pipe to fzf for interactive selection:
.B pathsearch | fzf
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success
.TP
.B 1
Error (invalid arguments, unreadable PATH, etc.)
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B PATH
Colon-separated list of directories to search.
